th Thomas Hooker) in 1635."],"variants":[{"name":"Clark","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>clerk</i>, <i>clark</i> ‘clerk, cleric, writer’ (Old French <i>clerc</i>; see   Clerc  ). The original sense was ‘man in a religious order, cleric, clergyman’. As all writing and secretarial work in medieval Christian Europe was normally done by members of the clergy, the term <i>clerk</i> came to mean ‘scholar, secretary, recorder, or penman’ as well as ‘cleric’. As a surname, it was particularly common for one who had taken only minor holy orders. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established.","Irish (Westmeath, Mayo): in Ireland the English surname was frequently adopted, partly by translation for <i>Ó Cléirigh</i>; see   Cleary  .","Americanized form of Dutch   De Klerk   or Flemish   De Clerck   or of variants of these names, and possibly also of French   Clerc  . Compare   Clerk   2 and   De Clark  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Clarke was born about 1460. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1548, in England, at the age of 89."},"et":{"Abt 1460–1548":"umbes 1460–1548","1488–Male":"1488–Surnud","1490–1550":"1490–1550","–Female":"Surnud","1460–1548":"1460–1548","Abt 1460":"umbes 1460","1488":"1488","1550":"1550","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1548":"1548","England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1460–1548":"noin 1460–1548","1488–Male":"1488–Kuollut","1490–1550":"1490–1550","–Female":"Kuollut","1460–1548":"1460–1548","Abt 1460":"noin 1460","1488":"1488","1550":"1550","1460":"1460","14